<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1631&amp;p=13977#p13977"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Doesn't the fact that we're emulating a machine wich they invented (and have patents for) make emulators illegal?<br /></div><br /><br />You seem to have fallen for the fantasies of many copyright/patent holders. These are state-granted monopolies originally created for the purpose of having <em>more</em> things that the public can do <em>whatever they damn well please</em> with, in the long-term. Neither grant any property rights, just monopoly on some <em>uses</em> of the ideas/implementations. The use of the term "property" in connection with these monopolies is an attempt to mislead people like us into mistakenly applying the concepts of property. They don't apply, since unlike property, copyrighted materials and patentable ideas can't be stolen, only shared and used.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Thu Jun 08, 2006 1:28 pm</p><hr />
