<div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The law doesn't have to be logical<br /></div><br /><br />And rarely is. I won't drag a political argument here, but I can name at least five areas of law that were created solely through racism, bigotry and corporate lobbying that have absolutely no positive value to society whatsoever. Why should laws based around greed be any different?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />In some countries, emulators are legal even if hardware clones are not because an algorithm running on generic computer hardware is not patentable.<br /></div><br /><br />Is that still the case? As far as I know, UNISYS' GIF patent was applicable not only in the US but also in European countries. But of course, Nintendo likely hasn't patented any of its algorithms used in their consoles. And they expire. Thank god Disney doesn't make consumer electronics.<br /><br />Anyway, since Bleem! won continuously in court, <em>and</em> their work was for sale, I'd say there's strong precedent for even modern emulators to be legal. However, you'd better have more money than the company suing you if you expect to avoid bankruptcy.<br />I'm surprised more companies don't take advantage of this. Why not have say, Sunny Delight sue Tropicana until they bankrupt? Sue them for made up stuff just to waste time and money until they fold. Hey, it worked great for Sony.<br /><br />On a related note, we could bypass the legality of ROMs (at least until they all fail from old age) by creating a USB "cart connector" that you attach real NES cartridges to. And then you'd be able to control the accesses to the cart through the emulator. Is there any reason this approach won't work? I imagine it would also be very helpful for reverse engineering weird special cart hardware.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=375">byuu</a> — Thu Jun 08, 200