<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1631&amp;p=13963#p13963"><![CDATA[
So we need to perfect the <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=656" class="postlink">"stop-n-swop"</a> method's reliability for dumping a cartridge (the poor man's CopyNES), then get Memblers to produce the boot cartridge and his serial adaptor cable that plugs into the joypad port.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I finally decided myself that download games that have been my mom more than 5 years ago or so cannot be illegal if there is no new production of the said game, even if this is false. This just seem logical.<br /></div><br /><br />The law doesn't have to be logical, mostly because it's largely historical and updates are kept as minimal as possible. Copyright was originally meant to expand the valuable public domain of intellectual creations by providing further economic benefits to creators, but it's been warped into a means of indefinite profit for the creator. Games which have been dormant can be brought back at any time, for example the ports to Game Boy Color and Game Boy Advance, and soon the Wii. The particular format of the games isn't in production anymore (NES cartridges), but the copyrighted work (the code and game characters) is still being maintained.<br /><br />I'm always trying to learn more about copyright law, so don't hesitate in correcting me.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Thu Jun 08, 2006 10:51 am</p><hr />
