<div class="quotetitle">WedNESday wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Wrong. If you write an emulator for the purpose of letting others play downloaded (or any illegal ROMs) then the emulator is illegal. Nintendo's own legal web page states so.<br /></div><br />Nintendo is biased. Nintendo states what it <em>wants</em> to be illegal. But in the United States, there's something called "substantial non-infringing use." For instance, VCRs may be used to mass-duplicate movies (obvious infringement), or they may be used to time-shift television programming (which the Supreme Court has labeled as fair use). Likewise, emulators are useful for 1. homebrew and 2. ROM images dumped with CopyNES. But if you <em>advertise</em> an emulator as useful with ROMs obtained through illegal means, then you're "inducing" infringement. The controlling case law is <em>Sony v. Universal</em> and <em>MGM v. Grokster</em>.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Jun 08, 2006 10:20 am</p><hr />
